e.g.  ekphrasis). Instead, it emphasizes literature's participation in visual culture at large and focuses on three areas of investigation: (1) the depiction of, for instance, visual perceptions in the literary mode of description, which is paramount to formatting the mental aspect of visual culture; (2) the readerly practice of visualising situations and events of the fictional world, which mediates between those mentefacts and techniques of writing; (3) textual visibilities which are grounded in materiality. The volume explores these three areas from a systematically integrated perspective and the essays include in-depth treatments of seminal examples taken from Western literatures (primarily English and German, but also French and American literature) from early modern times to the present. This book's aim is to work out literature's active role in shaping visual culture, thus demonstrating its relevance for "image studies".   aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 16. Mai 2019) 0aArt and literaturexHistory. 0aLiteraturexHistory and criticismxTheory, etc. 0aVisual perception in literature. 4aLiterarische Beschreibung. 4aLiterary description. 4aSchrift. 4aVisuelle Kultur. 4aliterature and visual culture. 4areaderly visualisation. 4avisible writings. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh1 aBodola, Ronja, eeditor.1 aIsekenmeier, Guido, eeditor.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2017z9783110540550oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE ENGLISH 2017z978311062526408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural and Area Studies 2017z9783110548198oZDB-23-DKU0 cEPUBz97831103873390 cprintz978311037794140uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9783110378030423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/